
[1]sconce

   SCONCE, n.

   1. A fort or bulwark; a work for defense. Obs.

   2. A hanging or projecting candlestick, generally with a mirror to
   reflect the light.

   Golden sconces hang upon the walls.

   3. The circular tube with a brim in a candlestick, into which the
   candle is inserted, that is, the support, the holder of the candle; and
   from this sense the candlestick, in the preceding definition, has its
   name.

   4. A fixed seat or shelf. [Local.]

                                 SCONCE, n.

   1. Sense; judgment; discretion or understanding. This sense has been in
   vulgar use in New England within my memory.

   2. The head; a low word.

   3. A mulet or fine.

        SCONCE, v.t. To mulet; to fine. [A low word and not in use.]
